  "prompt": "Can I get into grad school with 2 C's?",
  "response": "Yes, you can still get into graduate school with two C's on your transcript, but it will depend on several factors:\n\n1. **Overall GPA**: Graduate programs often look at your cumulative GPA. If your overall GPA is strong, having two C's might not be a dealbreaker.\n\n2. **Trend in Grades**: If the C's are from early in your academic career and your grades improved significantly in later years, admissions committees may view this positively as a sign of growth.\n\n3. **Relevance of the Courses**: If the C's are in courses that are not directly related to your field of study, they may carry less weight. However, if they are in key subjects for your intended graduate program, you may need to address them in your application.\n\n4. **Strength of the Rest of Your Application**: Other components of your application, such as letters of recommendation, statement of purpose, research experience, and GRE or other standardized test scores (if required), can help offset lower grades.\n\n5. **Program Competitiveness**: Some programs are more competitive than others. In highly competitive programs, even a couple of C's could be a disadvantage, while in less competitive programs, they may be more forgiving.\n\n6. **Explanation for the Grades**: If there were extenuating circumstances (e.g., personal issues, health problems) that led to the C's, you could address these in your personal statement or through a supplemental explanation to provide context.\n\nIn summary, while two C's are not ideal, they do not necessarily preclude you from getting into graduate school. Focus on building a strong overall application and highlighting your strengths.",
